{
  "summary": "Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) is a hybrid AI framework that integrates a retrieval component with a generative Large Language Model (LLM) to produce grounded, factually accurate responses. The core architecture relies on a dual-encoder model — most notably Dense Passage Retrieval (DPR) — where separate query and passage encoders are trained using contrastive learning. At inference time, pre-computed passage embeddings are stored in a FAISS index and retrieved via cosine similarity, enabling efficient semantic search. The retrieved documents are then passed as context to the generative LLM, which conditions its output on this external knowledge. RAG can also employ sparse retrieval methods such as BM25, though dense retrievers like DPR outperform BM25 by 9-18% on open-domain QA benchmarks. By grounding generation in retrieved evidence, RAG significantly reduces hallucination rates (from 20-30% down to 5-12%) and factual errors (by 40-60%) on knowledge-intensive tasks such as NaturalQuestions and TriviaQA. Advanced chunking strategies, such as semantic chunking based on embedding similarity, further improve retrieval precision by 15-25%. However, RAG introduces new failure modes including retrieval failures — where irrelevant or missing documents degrade generation quality — and residual hallucination when retrieved context is insufficient or misleading. Overall, RAG represents a foundational architecture for building reliable, knowledge-grounded language systems.",
